   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "29eeb48a-6753-427e-b536-380567db8fd8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "Here are two versions of the \"Hello, World!\" code in C#: one using the **modern, simplest syntax** (recommended for beginners) and another using the **classic class structure**.\n",
      "\n",
      "***\n",
      "\n",
      "## 🚀 Version 1: Modern Console App (The Easiest Way)\n",
      "\n",
      "In modern C# (.NET Core 3.0+), you can use \"Top-Level Statements,\" which means you don't need to wrap your code in a large `class` or `Main` method—you just write the instructions directly.\n",
      "\n",
      "```csharp\n",
      "// Program.cs\n",
      "\n",
      "Console.WriteLine(\"Hello, World!\");\n",
      "```\n",
      "\n",
      "### How it works:\n",
      "*   **`Console`**: This is a built-in class that represents the command prompt (the console). It allows your program to interact with text and input/output.\n",
      "*   **`.WriteLine()`**: This is a method belonging to the `Console` class. It prints the string you provide inside the parentheses, followed by a newline character.\n",
      "\n",
      "***\n",
      "\n",
      "## 📚 Version 2: Classic Structure (The Traditional Way)\n",
      "\n",
      "If your instructor or textbook uses older syntax, you might be required to wrap everything in a `class` and a `Main` method. This structure is still fundamental to understanding C#.\n",
      "\n",
      "```csharp\n",
      "using System;\n",
      "\n",
      "public class Program\n",
      "{\n",
      "    // The Main method is where execution always begins\n",
      "    public static void Main(string[] args)\n",
      "    {\n",
      "        Console.WriteLine(\"Hello, World!\");\n",
      "    }\n",
      "}\n",
      "```\n",
      "\n",
      "### Key Differences:\n",
      "*   **`using System;`**: This line tells the compiler that you plan to use functionality from the standard `System` library (which contains the `Console` class).\n",
      "*   **`public class Program`**: All code must live inside a container called a \"class.\" We named our class `Program`.\n",
      "*   **`static void Main(string[] args)`**: This is the **entry point**. When you run the program, the computer starts execution here.\n",
      "\n",
      "***\n",
      "\n",
      "### ✅ Recommendation:\n",
      "If you are just starting out and using modern tooling (like Visual Studio or VS Code with the .NET SDK), use **Version 1** (Top-Level Statements). It makes learning C# much faster!\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
